Macedonians voted in a referendum on Sunday if they want the country's name changed to the "North Macedonia Republic", a move that would settle a decade-old dispute with Greece, which was opposed to its accession to the European Union and NATO.
Greece, which includes a province called Macedonia, claims that the name of the neighbouring country represents a claim on its territory and has opposed its accession to the EU and NATO.
The two governments agreed in June on the proposed new name, but opposing nationalists argue that this change would undermine the ethnic identity of Macedonia's majority Slavic population.
President Gjorge Ivanov said he would not vote in the referendum and that a boycott campaign had cast doubt on voter turnout, with the minimum 50% threshold needed to validate the referendum possibly not being reached.
The question on the referendum ballot will be: “Are you in agreement with joining the EU and NATO, accepting the agreement with Greece?”
Proponents of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, say it is a price Macedonia, one of the countries that resulted from the breakup of Yugoslavia, has to pay in order to be accepted into entities such as the EU and NATO.
“I am here today to vote for the future of the country, for the young people of Macedonia to live freely under the umbrella of the European Union, because this means safer lives for all of us,” said Olivera Georgijevska, 79, in Skopje.
Although it is not legally binding, enough members of parliament have said they will respect the result of the vote to make it decisive.
For the name to be changed, a two-thirds quorum in parliament is required.
The state election commission said no irregularities were reported until 1 p.m.
However, turnout was only 16%, compared to 34% in the last parliamentary elections in 2016 when 66% of those with the right to vote voted.
“I came to vote for my children and for our place in Europe,” said Gjose Tanevski, 62, a voter in Skopje, the country’s capital.
On 30 September 2018, Macedonian Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and their son Dushko voted for the referendum on changing Macedonia's name, which will allow it to join NATO and enter the European Union.
In front of the parliament in Skopje, 54-year-old Vladimir Kavardarkov prepared a small-sized stage and pulled chairs in front of the tents erected by those who would boycott the referendum.
"We support NATO and the EU, but we want to join them with our heads up, not through the back door," Kavadarkov said.
“We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
If we are not wanted under the name of Macedonia, we can move to other countries, such as China and Russia, and we can become part of the Eurasian Union.”
Prime Minister Zaev said NATO membership would bring much-needed investment to Macedonia, which has an unemployment rate of more than 20%.
“I think the majority will be in favour of changing the name, because more than 80% of our citizens are in favour of joining NATO and the EU,” Zaev said after casting his vote.
He said a result in favor of changing the name would be “confirmation of our future.”
According to a survey published last Monday by the Institute for Policy Research, between 30% and 43% of citizens with the right to vote will participate in the referendum, below the required number of participants.
According to another poll, conducted by Telma TV in Macedonia, 57% of respondents plan to vote on Sunday.
Of these, 70% said they would vote for the change.
For the referendum to be valid, the turnout must be 50% plus one vote.
The failure of the referendum would be the first major blow to the pro-Western government’s policy since it took office in May last year.
