Throughout Bolivia, which has no waterfront, the memory of a coastline lost to Chile in a bloody 19th-century resource conflict is still alive – just like the desire to sail back into the Pacific Ocean.
These hopes are probably at their highest level in decades, as Bolivia awaits a ruling by the International Court of Justice on October 1, after five years of deliberations.
“Bolivia has the necessary momentum, a spirit of unity and serenity and, of course, awaits the result with a positive outlook,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will watch the ICJ decision on big screens across the country, hoping that the Hague court will rule in favor of Bolivia’s claim and that, after decades of firm talks, Chile is forced to negotiate the granting of a sovereign exit to the sea, Bolivia.
