John Edward: Language skills essential for global citizens
Independent schools in Scotland hold a record for academic excellence, and this has continued into 2018 with another set of outstanding exam scores, which is supported by individual and collective successes in sports, arts, music and other community endeavors.
With over 30,000 students in Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide services at the highest level to their students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for high school and higher education, their chosen careers and their place as global citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a special school curriculum, we note that modern languages continue to be a popular and desired subject of choice within schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, your words will reach his mind.
If you speak to him in his own language, the words reach his heart.”
This is a strong reminder that we can’t just rely on English when we want to build relationships and trust people from other countries.
Based on the recent results of this year’s competition, we note that foreign languages are at the top of the rankings, with the highest promotion rates in independent schools.
A total of 68% of students who have studied foreign languages have obtained a Higher grade A certificate.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72% of students obtained a Higher grade A certificate in Mandarin; also 72% of those studying German, 69% of those studying French and 63% of those studying Spanish obtained such a certificate.
This demonstrates that independent schools in Scotland support languages as vital skills that children and young people will certainly need in the future.
Now, foreign languages, as a subject, are held the same way as STEM (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) subjects in independent school curricula and in other fields.
A survey conducted by the UK’s Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 found that for the reasons employers gave for fighting for vacancies, 17% were attributed to a shortage of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly becoming imperative for preparing young people for their future careers.
With more job opportunities requiring foreign languages, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
No matter what career someone chooses, if they have learned a second language, they will have a real advantage in the future, having such a lifelong skill.
The ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will automatically put a multilingual person ahead of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to conduct a conversation, and French was the only two-digit language spoken, 15%.
That’s why investing in language learning is important for children today.
Having more languages, especially in developing countries, children will be more likely to find meaningful jobs.
In Scotland, each school will teach other languages.
A number of schools will focus on more modern classical languages, while others will learn the languages that are considered to be the most important for the UK when looking ahead to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child’s interest is, there will always be multiple languages of choice within independent schools, with teachers who are specialized in this field.
Independent schools in Scotland are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and encourage them with the skills they need to succeed, whatever the future may be.
It cannot be denied at this time, in a global business environment, that languages continue to be vital to the future of the country, so it must be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages should indeed be considered "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
It has to be done (it has to be done).
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
