North Korea’s foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that the extension of sanctions would deepen distrust in the United States and that it was impossible for his country to unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly of the global council that North Korea had implemented “significant measures to prove its good faith” last year, such as halting nuclear testing and missile testing, dismantling the nuclear test site, and commitment to non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and technology.
"However, we do not see any appropriate response from the United States," he said.
“If we can’t trust the United States, we won’t trust our national security capabilities, and under such circumstances, we can’t unilaterally disarm ourselves first.”
Although Ri echoed North Korea's familiar objections to Washington's resistance to a "step-by-step" approach to denuclearization, according to which North Korea would be rewarded if it took gradual steps, his statement seemed significant because it did not directly reject unilateral denuclearization, as Pyongyang did in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at a first-ever summit between a current U.S. president and North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, where Kim pledged to make progress toward a “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula,” while Trump offered assurances on North Korea’s security.
North Korea sought an official end to the 1950-1953 Korean War, but the United States said Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
In addition, Washington has failed to heed calls for easing harsh international sanctions on North Korea.
“The United States is insisting on the ‘denuclearization first’ option and is increasing the pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal in a coercive way, even objecting to the ‘declaration of the end of the war,’” Ri said.
“The impression that sanctions can bring us to our knees is an illusion that only people who don’t know us have.
