Ri did not mention plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump that the U.S. leader referred to at the United Nations earlier this week.
In contrast, the minister highlighted the three meetings between Kim and Moon Jae-in, the president of South Korea, in the last five months, adding: "If the issue of denuclearization had been negotiated with South Korea and not with the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have reached this impasse."
Even under these circumstances, the tone of Ri’s speech was very different from that of last year’s speech, when he told the U.N. General Assembly that targeting U.S. territory with missiles from North Korea was inevitable after “Evil President” Trump called Kim a “missile man” on a suicide mission.
