Harvard students take classes on how to get enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year encourages students to sleep more, in an attempt to combat the growing “macho” culture that makes them undergo “all night” learning sessions energized with plenty of caffeine.
A scientist has discovered that students at the world’s most prestigious university often don’t even master the basic concepts of how they should take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, is the one who created the course, which is believed to be the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to create the course after giving a lecture on the impact of lack of sleep on the ability to learn.
“At the end, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why am I being told this just now, in the last year?’
She told me that she had never been told about the importance of sleep, which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, introduced for the first time this year, explains to students essential concepts of how good sleep habits help improve academic and athletic performance, as well as overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students were seriously deprived of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course may involve a number of interactive tasks.
In a section, students can click on coffee cups, curtains, sports pants and books to be told what the effects of caffeine and light are and how athletic performance is affected by sleep deficiency, but also about the importance of a sleep program.
In another section, participants were told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression and cancer.
A campus map, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily schedule.
“We know that we can’t change students’ behavior instantly.
But we believe they have the right to know, just as anyone has the right to know what the health effects of smoking are,” Czeisler said.
The culture that makes students proud to have learned all night still exists, he says, adding that modern technology and growing pressure on students have made sleep deprivation a growing problem.
Sufficient sleep, of good quality, should be a student’s “secret weapon” to combat stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said, and even to avoid weight gain, because sleep deprivation makes the brain believe that the body is hungry, which makes students feel that they are constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler create the course after attending one of his courses in his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to promote a course for all students.
The next step, he hopes, is to require all postgraduate students to complete a similar degree program before enrolling at this institution where competition is fierce.
Professor Czeisler advised students to set an alarm to know when it’s time to go to bed, as well as for waking time, and to know what the harmful effects of “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LEDs are, which can disturb the circadian rhythm and cause difficulties when they try to fall asleep.
