National Trust spies on the secret life of bats
New research being conducted on a property in the Scottish Highlands wants to reveal how bats use the environment to hunt their prey.
It is hoped that the findings will reveal new things about the behavior of these unusual flying mammals and help future conservation activities.
The study by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland will look at common dwarf bats and pygmy bats, as well as ear bats and water bats from the Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed in key locations around the property to track bat activity throughout the season.
The NHS team and volunteers will also conduct mobile studies using manual detectors.
Specialized audio analysis of all recordings will estimate the frequency of sounds made by bats and what species emit certain sounds.
A habitat map and a report will also be produced to create a detailed, scaled-up picture of their behaviour in the environment.
Rob Dewar, a nature conservation consultant for NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of the habitat are most important to bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as creating lawns, and which is the best way to maintain forest meadows for bats and other associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and across the UK have declined considerably over the past century.
They are threatened by construction and development work affecting their nests, but also by habitat loss.
And wind turbines and public lighting are risks, as are traps for flies and some chemical treatments for building materials, but also attacks by domestic cats.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, because they hunt at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to accurately identify insects and obstacles on their flight path.
NTS, which is responsible for caring for more than 270 historic buildings, 38 major parks and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, is thinking very seriously about bats.
They have ten trained experts, who periodically conduct surveys, control the nests, and sometimes carry out rescue missions.
The organization even created the first and only bat reserve in Scotland, on the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, where eight out of ten bat species in Scotland are found.
The manager of the estate, David Thompson, says that this is the ideal territory for bats.
“Here at Threade, the area is great for bats,” he says.
“We have old buildings, a lot of old trees and a perfect habitat.
But there’s a lot we don’t know about bats, so the work we do here and elsewhere will help us understand what they need to multiply.”
It emphasizes the importance of looking for bats before performing maintenance work on properties, as the mere unintentional destruction of a maternal nest could kill up to 400 females and cubs, which can destroy the entire local population.
Bats are protected, and killing, harassing or disturbing them, as well as destroying their nests, are prohibited actions.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish official with the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help them.
She said: “We still have a lot to learn about bats and we don’t know how populations are evolving for many of our species.”
