Syria Ready for Refugee Return, Foreign Minister Says
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and calls for help to rebuild the country ravaged by a war that has lasted for more than seven years.
During his speech at the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said the situation in the country is improving.
“Today, the conditions on the ground are more stable and secure, thanks to the progress made in combating terrorism,” he said.
The government continues to rehabilitate areas destroyed by terrorists so that things return to normal.
The existing conditions allow refugees to return voluntarily to the country they were forced to leave due to terrorism and unilateral economic measures affecting their daily lives and livelihoods.
The United Nations estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country since the war broke out in 2011.
Six million people who continue to live in the country are in need of humanitarian assistance.
Al-Moualem said the Syrian regime would be happy to receive help to rebuild the devastated country.
But he stressed that conditional assistance or aid from countries sponsored by the insurgency will not be accepted.
