Red tide news: concentrations decreased in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The Florida Wildlife Commission’s latest report shows an overall drop in red tide concentrations for certain areas of the Gulf of Tampa.
According to the Commission, uneven inflorescence conditions are reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties – suggesting decreased concentrations.
This red tide inflorescence extends over a coastal area of about 210 km from northern Pinellas County to southern Lee County.
The spots can be found about 16 km off Hillsborough County, but in fewer places than last week.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
The average concentrations found in or off Pinellas County were reported last week, as were low to high concentrations in Hillsborough County, background to high concentrations in Manatee County, background to high concentrations in or off Sarasota County, background to high concentrations in or off Leghorn County, background concentrations in or off Leghorn County, background to medium concentrations in or off Leghorn County.
Airway irritation continues to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No cases of airway irritation have been reported in northwest Florida in the past week.
